In addition, the effect of CDs nanofluid on the injection pressure of saturated oil cores was further investigated(Fig. 5
                        ), and the effect of core permeability on the pressure reduction performance was explored(Table 2
                        ). It can be seen that CDs nanofluid produced a greater pressure reduction rate of 35.74% in the core of saturated oil, accompanied by the output of more oil droplets. This is because the CDs drive out more oil phase, which results in less remaining oil film in the pore space, the fluid flow channel is widened, and the resistance is reduced spontaneously. The effect of core permeability on CDs nanofluid’s pressure reduction performance is shown in Table 2. In the permeability range of 0.17 ∼ 5.05mD, the CDs nanofluids have a sound performance of pressure reduction and enhance oil recovery. The highest pressure reduction rate of 35.45% is achieved in the core with the permeability of 0.25mD, at which time the recovery factor was improved by ∼ 21% compared with water flooding. When the core permeability is very low (0.17 mD) or high (5.05 mD), the pressure reduction rate decreases slightly, but the change is insignificant. This may be because the CDs adsorbed on both the solid and oil phase surfaces, which modulated the interfacial properties, resulting in the oil film attached to the rock wall being more easily stripped off during the water flushing. Moreover, the CDs size is small enough to enter the finer pore throats and effectively displace the residual oil film, thus enhancing the oil recovery and reducing injection pressure.
